          "body": "The LORD's second sentence in verse 2 is a rhetorical question that functions as the most compressed testimony to God's prior grace in the entire chapter: 'Is this not a brand plucked from the fire?' A brand is a piece of burning wood, rescued mid-flame — not pristine, not repaired, but saved. It is still charred, still smoking, still bearing the marks of the fire it came from. Amos 4:11 uses the same image for Israel's near-total destruction in judgment. Joshua and the returned community are not a success story; they are survivors of the Babylonian furnace, still bearing exile's scorch-marks. The rhetorical question ('Is this not...?') expects the answer 'Yes, of course it is.' The brand's condition — still visibly burnt — is precisely the argument for why it must not be abandoned now. God has already paid the price of pulling it out. To discard it at the accuser's request would be to waste the rescue. The pastoral power of this image for the post-exilic community is immense: you are not disqualified by your history of judgment; you are identified by the God who pulled you out of it. Charles Spurgeon, preaching on this verse, called it 'the argument of mercy' — God's past investment in rescuing the sinner becomes the argument for His present commitment to preserving him."
